STEP 1ï¸âƒ£ Install Elasticsearch
Add Elastic repo
curl -fsSL https://artifacts.elastic.co/GPG-KEY-elasticsearch | sudo apt-key add -
sudo apt-add-repository "deb https://artifacts.elastic.co/packages/8.x/apt stable main"
sudo apt update

Install Elasticsearch
sudo apt install elasticsearch -y

Start Elasticsearch
sudo systemctl enable elasticsearch
sudo systemctl start elasticsearch

Verify
curl http://localhost:9200


âœ… Elasticsearch running

STEP 2ï¸âƒ£ Install Kibana
sudo apt install kibana -y
sudo systemctl enable kibana
sudo systemctl start kibana


Access:

http://<server-ip>:5601


âœ… Kibana UI opens

STEP 3ï¸âƒ£ Install Filebeat
sudo apt install filebeat -y

STEP 4ï¸âƒ£ Configure Filebeat (IMPORTANT)
Open config
sudo nano /etc/filebeat/filebeat.yml

4.1 Enable log input
filebeat.inputs:
- type: log
  enabled: true
  paths:
    - /var/log/*.log


ğŸ“Œ This means:

â€œCollect all .log files from /var/logâ€

4.2 Configure Elasticsearch output
output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["localhost:9200"]


ğŸ“Œ Filebeat sends logs directly to Elasticsearch

4.3 Disable Logstash (if not using)
# output.logstash:
#   hosts: ["localhost:5044"]

STEP 5ï¸âƒ£ Enable Filebeat Modules (RECOMMENDED)

Modules = prebuilt log parsers + dashboards

Enable system logs
sudo filebeat modules enable system


This collects:

syslog

auth.log

Load dashboards into Kibana
sudo filebeat setup


ğŸ“Š Dashboards auto-created

STEP 6ï¸âƒ£ Start Filebeat
sudo systemctl enable filebeat
sudo systemctl start filebeat

Verify
sudo systemctl status filebeat

STEP 7ï¸âƒ£ Verify Logs in Kibana

Open Kibana

Go to Discover

Select index:

filebeat-*


ğŸ‰ You should see logs!

STEP 8ï¸âƒ£ How it Works (VERY IMPORTANT)
Real flow:
/var/log/syslog
      â†“
Filebeat reads line by line
      â†“
Adds metadata (host, timestamp)
      â†“
Sends JSON to Elasticsearch
      â†“
Kibana queries Elasticsearch
